lations with China. Chou addresses the pivotal but previously unacknowledged history of artistic and intellectual exchange between the varying religious, linguistic, and cultural traditions of the region. The reimagining of Mount Wutai was a fluid endeavor that proved central to the cosmopolitanism of the Qing Empire, and the mountain range became a unique site of shared diplomacy, trade, and religious devotion between different constituents, as well as a spiritual bridge between China and Tibet.A compelling exploration of the changing meaning and significance of one of the world's great religious sites, Mount Wutai offers an important new framework for understanding Buddhist sacred geography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aBuddhism and culture. 0aBuddhist templeszChinazWutai Mountains. 0aCultural landscapeszChinazWutai Mountains. 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh  aAmdo.  aApparitions (TV series).  aBeijing.  aBhikkhu.  aBodhisattva.  aBuddhism.  aBuddhist art.  aBuddhist cosmology.  aBuddhist pilgrimage.  aBuddhist symbolism.  aBuddhist temple.  aBuddhist texts.  aChakravartin.  aChan Buddhism.  aChengde.  aChengdu.  aChina proper.  aChina.  aChinese Buddhism.  aChinese language.  aChinese literature.  aCloister.  aConfucianism.  aCosmography.  aDalai Lama.  aDeity.  aDunhuang.  aEthnological Museum of Berlin.  aEvocation.  aGazetteer.  aGuanyin.  aGyatso.  aHagiography.  aIconography.  aIllustration.  aImperial Preceptor.  aIncarnation (Christianity).  aIncarnation.  aInner Asia.  aInner Mongolia.  aJokhang.  aKangyur.  aKhenpo Sodargye.  aKhenpo.  aKumbum.  aLarung Gar.  aLhasa.  aLiterature.  aMahayana.  aMissionary.  aMogao Caves.  aMonastery.  aMongols.  aMount Wutai.  aMountain range.  aNarr